<font class="head">Innovations 2002</font>
<br>
As the most widely renowned consumer technology awards program, the Innovations 2002 awards program recognizes outstanding achievement in product design. Sponsored by the Consumer Electronics Association (CEA) and endorsed by the Industrial Designers Society of America (IDSA), Innovations will showcase the winners in the Las Vegas Hilton.

<br><br>



<!-- Thursday Jan 10content starts here -->

<font class="righttext">
<img src="/global_images/techthurs.gif"><br>

Imagine equipping your home with networked systems that can control everything from distributing TV and Internet content to programming your alarm systems. Return home after work and simultaneously adjust the temperature while tuning in your favorite digital TV broadcast and checking your e-mail. This networked home can be installed easily and inexpensively today. 
<br><br>
The Consumer Electronics Association (CEA) defines a home network as one that facilitates communication among the appliances, home systems, entertainment products and information devices in a home, so they can share information. This allows users to control home systems. The home network includes lighting, audio/video system components, temperature control, security, telephone/communications, the personal computer network, Internet service, utilities and power and even controlling drapes and blinds.
<br><br>
You don’t even have to be at home to control appliances and other devices. Logging onto a password-protected site via a Web browser, a user can check on such things while away from home. Virtually any digital source—a DVD, a CD player or a TV—can be controlled through a handheld remote or even by voice. Many products now allow appliances, home systems and electronic devices to communicate through dedicated wires, wirelessly via radio frequency or through a home's existing wiring.
<br><br>
Even the simple home phone of the past is evolving, thanks to broadband applications. Broadband gives consumers the ability to connect to the Internet almost instantly, load graphics quickly and watch video more easily. The most common types of broadband transmission are digital subscriber lines (DSL) and cable wiring (as in cable modems). Telephone companies, who have a jump on the data side, are pushing DSL, a technology that enables high-speed data transfer over existing phone lines. The FCC estimates that DSL and cable modems will have comparable subscriber levels by 2007.
<br><br>
The 2002 CES is the place to see the latest in home networking technology and the products that work within these systems.  
<br><br>
