<br><br>
<a name="wireless"></a>
<font class="righttext">
<img src="/global_images/techtues.gif"><br>

Now, more than ever, consumer electronics are everywhere. From the home to the office, and all points in between, consumers can be entertained, informed and in contact from almost anywhere.
<br><br>
A new generation of wireless phones, pagers and personal digital assistants (PDAs) are giving consumers enhanced capabilities, ranging from Internet browsing and Web-based applications to multimedia functions. Wireless phones, PDAs and other pocket-size communicators stand on the brink of an age where mobile computing and telephony converge. 
<br><br>
The emerging mobile multimedia market offers consumers the ability to travel safer and more efficiently than ever before. Global positioning systems (GPS) can provide you with the most direct route to your destination, simply by plugging in the address. With rear-seat video systems, parents can entertain children on long road trips by using monitors built into headrests or ceilings. And when it comes to music, newly debuted digital satellite radio offers listeners the choice of up to 100 channels of music, news, information and other programming.
<br><br>
Meanwhile, the first IDB-based cars are gearing up for production. IDB (Intelligent Transportation System Data Bus) is a plug-and-play technology that enables IDB devices to talk to each other, sharing information. When a driver is stranded, for instance, the car can call for help through a mobile phone and give the car's location automatically. 
<br><br>
The reach of mobile and wireless communication, entertainment and information products extend infinitely - and the 2002 CES is no exception.  <br>
Here’s a look at what you won’t want to miss:
<ul>
<li>LVCC Gold Parking Lot for the <b>Mercedes Benz Tech Drive</b>
<li>LVCC North Hall for <b>mobile electronics</b> including <b>car audio/video, satellite radio and in-car information systems</b>
<li>LVCC North Hall for the <b>Intelligent Transportation System Data Bus (IDB) Pavilion</b> sponsored by the IDB Forum 
<li>LVCC North Hall for the <b>Digital Car Showroom</b>
<li>LVCC Central Hall upper level meeting rooms for <b>home information and wireless</b>
<li>LVCC Central Hall Main Level Meeting Rooms for <b>mobile electronics exhibitors</b>
<li>LVCC South Hall 2 Lower Level for the <b>Emerging Technologies Launchpad</b>
<li>LVCC South Hall 3-4 upper level for <b>wireless accessories and communications</b>
<li>LVCC South Hall 3-4 upper level for the <b>Bluetooth Showcase</b>
<li>LVCC South Hall 3-4 upper level for the <b>Wi-Fi Pavilion</b> and <b>Palm Solutions Providers Pavilion</b>
<li>LVCC South Hall 3-4 upper level for <b>telephony</b>
</ul>

<font size="1"><a href="#top">back to the top</a></font>

<font class="head"><a href="/conferences/Session_detail.asp?menuItem=1&subMenuItem=2&tabName=Attendee&id_session=SS2">Wireless SuperSession</font></a><br>
<font class="subhead">Tuesday, January 8, 2002, 2:00-3:30pm, North Hall LVCC N250</font><br>
The wireless category is leading the convergence pack with the integration of phone, Internet and computer into a single device; but which device will win consumers over: handset, PDA, pager or notebook? How will future devices evolve: PDAs as cell phones? Cell phones as digital cameras? Cell phones as MP3 players? And what are content and service providers bringing to the table? Leading wireless executives discuss the opportunities - and challenges - facing the industry in the next 12 months.<br><br>

<font class="head"><a href="/conferences/keynotes.asp?menuItem=1&subMenuItem=1&tabName=Attendee#sprint">Industry Keynote Address</a></font>
