<font class="head">CEA Wireless Division</font><br>
Formed in 2001, CEA’s Wireless Division aims to bring together wireless device manufacturers and related businesses to develop programs and services that will increase retail sales of wireless and handheld products, as well as advance the development of convergent products and technologies for the consumer market. <br><br>
Here’s a look at some of the CEA programs and services specifically designed for the Wireless industry:<ul>
<li>The Wireless Retail Training and Certification Working Group will create education programs to help retail managers and sales personnel better sell wireless and handheld products. 
<li>A National Retailer Database Working Group is creating a database of wireless retailers for the purpose of marketing CEA programs and events and conducting industry-specific research. The training and certification program will be the primary focus of the promotional activities. 
<li>With assistance from the Research Working Group and CEA's market research staff, the division will produce surveys and reports of interest to the wireless community. Most recently, CEA produced the Wireless Device Usage Report, a detailed look at handset, hand-held and accessory usage in the U.S. 
<li>Through the Promotions Committee, CEA's communications department and wireless industry leaders will work together to build marketing campaigns that will advance the division's messages both to the wireless community and the consumer market. </ul>

<a href="http://www.ce.org/Market_Overview/wireless/wireless1.asp" class="bodylink">Click here</a> for more information on the Wireless Division, as well as other CEA initiatives.
<br><br>
<font class="head">From the latest issue of <i>Consumer Electronics Vision Magazine</i> <br> 
“The Digital Adventures of Wireless Woman”</font>
<br><br>
Finding new, better ways to do old things has become the mantra of the digital age. Until recently, “better” in the consumer electronics vernacular, usually meant faster, smaller, lighter and less expensive. But in the post-20th century economy, better must also encompass anytime, any place connectivity: the ability to roam around with a mobile device and still have a high-speed hook-up to the Internet or corporate files, without cables or configuration problems.  <br>

| <a href="http://www.ce.org/vision_magazine/editions/2002/janfebmar/p06.asp" class="bodylink">Click here to continue</a> |<br><br>

<font class="head"><i>Digital America</i></font><br><br>

<b>Wireless</b><br>
For anyone who travels for business or pleasure, today's wireless devices give you access to airline and hotel information, driving directions and e-mail and without having to lug around a notebook computer and find a phone line to plug it into. <br>

| <a href="http://www.ce.org/digitalamerica/wireless/default.asp" class="bodylink">A complete overview of the wireless industry is available here</a> |<br><br>


<b>Mobile Electronics</b>
The mobile electronics category is poised to explode on several fronts during the next couple of years as wireless technology, multimedia and telematics converge to create exciting new applications for consumers. Thanks to emerging standards and advances in digital technology, consumers can look forward to enjoying all the entertainment and information functionality they experience at home while on the road. The digital revolution will deliver a safer driving environment for consumers as well, from vehicle security to navigation assistance. <br>
| <a href="http://www.ce.org/digitalamerica/mobile/default.asp" class="bodylink">For a complete overview of the mobile electronics industry, click here</a> |
<br><br>



<font size="1"><a href="#top">back to the top</a></font>



<br><br>


<a name="fashion"></a>


<img src="/global_images/womanphone.jpg" align="left"><img src="/global_images/tech_hi.gif"><br>
From cell phones to computers to home audio equipment, the importance of good design has become increasingly prevalent in the consumer electronics marketplace. In addition to wanting the latest technology in their homes and workplaces, consumers are focusing on "the look", using product uniqueness and design to stand out from the crowd, to express themselves and achieve their personal identity. Perennially  significant, fashion has become a market driver. Consumers now appreciate, not only the thought and ingenuity of the technology inside, but the style and design influences responsible for the look of the products as well.
<br><br>
The convergence of fashion and technology definitely will be underway at the 2002 CES, from fashion showcases to the latest products from manufacturers. 
<br><br>
Here's a look at what you don't want to miss:
<br><br>
<font class="head">First Annual CES Fashion Show Extravaganza</font><br>
<font class="subhead">January 8-11, 2002, a total of nine live shows will run during CES, LVCC Grand Lobby</font><br>
The Grand Lobby of the Las Vegas Convention Center (LVCC) will be transformed into a high-tech fashion environment as CES showcases style in consumer electronics. Using runway models, pre-recorded video product features, live video projection, energetic music and lighting, CES will highlight the most stylish CE products and the apparel and accessories that complement them.<br><br>&nbsp;<br>


<font class="head">Digital Entertainment Village</font><br>
<font class="subhead">Las Vegas Convention Center, South 3</font><br>

This is the place to see and test the coolest display of interactive audio innovations. Experience the fusion of interactive entertainment, digital audio, and out-of-this-world imaging advances at the Digital Entertainment Village. 
<table width="90%" align="center"><tr><td class="noshadow">
<b>The Game and Interactive Entertainment Zone</b><br>
<i>Sponsored by IE Magazine</i><br>
Electronic gaming and interactive entertainment are colliding. See it first at the 2002 International CES, the only platform that delivers the most comprehensive lineup of entertainment platforms and distribution channels. 
<br><br>
<b>MP3 & Internet Audio Zone</b><br>
Get hip to the latest buzz in the world of downloadable digital audio, as advances in digital technology take audio into a new age. Explore the convergence of the entertainment, computer and Internet industries. See which emerging companies offer the hottest products, newest features and best price points. 
</td></tr>
</table><br>
<font class="head">Digital Home Appliances Pavilion</font><br>
<i>Sponsored by Appliance Magazine</i><br>
<font class="subhead">Las Vegas Convention Center, South 3-4</font><br>

Check out a new look at products at the core of the networked home at the Digital Home Appliance Pavilion, sponsored by Appliance Magazine. Discover the products and technology behind Internet-ready, "smart appliances." Companies include Broadmax Technologies, COMMAX, DoBox Inc., First2Hit Ltd, Home Automation Inc., Home Automated Living and Tonight's Menu. <br><br>

<font class="head">Innovations 2002</font><br>
Las Vegas Hilton<br>
As the most widely renowned consumer technology awards program, the Innovations 2002 awards program recognizes outstanding achievement in product design. Sponsored by the Consumer Electronics Association (CEA) and endorsed by the Industrial Designers Society of America (IDSA), Innovations will showcase the winners in the Las Vegas Hilton.
<br><br>
<font class="head">TechTV's Best of CES Awards</font><br>
TechTV will pick the hottest products in 10 workstyle and lifestyle categories on-site at CES. Winners will be announced at the TechTV Awards Reception on Thursday, January 10 at 5:30pm in LVCC Room S222.<br><br>

